best_score = 0

for C in [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100]:
    for solver in ['newton-cg', 'sag', 'saga', 'lbfgs']:
        logreg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, multi_class='multinomial',
                                   C=C, solver=solver, penalty='l2')
        logreg.fit(X_train_scaled, Y_train)
        score = logreg.score(X_valid_scaled, Y_valid)
        if score > best_score:
            best_score = score
            best_params = {'C':C, 'solver':solver}
logreg = LogisticRegression(**best_params)
logreg.fit(X_trainval_scaled, Y_trainval)
train_score = logreg.score(X_trainval_scaled, Y_trainval)
test_score = logreg.score(X_test_scaled, Y_test)

print("Best score on val set: {:.2f}".format(best_score))
print("Best parameters: ", best_params)
print("Train test score with best parameters: {:.2f}".format(train_score))
print("Test set score with best parameters: {:2f}".format(test_score))

95+257+172/946 % = 55.3%¶

  1. we have used logistic regression with c values as [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100] which controls regularization, we found 100 to be the most accurate.
  2. different solvers were used ['newton-cg', 'sag', 'saga', 'lbfgs'] out of which newton-cg has best accuracy.
  3. max iterations were taken as 1000 and multi_class as 'multinomial' as there is more than two classes and penalty as l2 which takes sum of squares.
  4. observations - we can see we have 55.3% accuracy which is low indicating the model requires more finetuning.

In [60]:
# Build the model

theta1 = 0
theta0 = 0

alpha = 0.0001  # Learning Rate
epochs = 1000  # Number of iterations to perform gradient descent

m = float(len(X_train)) # Number of elements in X

cost_history = []
# Performing Gradient Descent 
for i in range(epochs): 
    Y_pred = theta1 * X_train + theta0   
    temp1 = (-1/m) * sum(X_train * (Y_train - Y_pred))  
    temp0 = (-1/m) * sum(Y_train - Y_pred)   
    theta1 = theta1 - alpha * temp1   
    theta0 = theta0 - alpha * temp0   
    cost = (1/2*m) * sum((Y_train - Y_pred)**2)
    cost_history.append(cost)

print("Mean squared error = %.2f" % mean_squared_error(Y_test, Y_pred))

# Explained variance score: 1 is perfect prediction
print('Variance score = %.2f' % r2_score(Y_test, Y_pred))

Mean squared error = 0.11
Variance score = 0.98
  1. age was selected as target because ring had high correlation with age
  2. linear regression with gradient descent was used
  3. we have found theta values and alpha is 0.0001 with epochs 1000 , 1000 was chosen as after 400 we dont see any diffrence in cost func
  4. we found that mean squared error was 0.11 and variance score was 0.98 so we chose gradient descent as a regularizastion .
  5. quantity - we can see mean squared error is low and variance is also low indicating low bias and low variance of the model.
  6. observation - The model seems to perform good with test data indicating this model can be used for real life purposes.
